{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657983"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:39:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:39:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20693"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20693","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20693"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.55,0.05,0,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13569"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94885"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13569"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20693"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77892"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11657"},{"type":"tags","id":"12461"},{"type":"tags","id":"12552"},{"type":"tags","id":"12571"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32554"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32555"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94885"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents with chest pain, hypertension (180/110 mmHg), tachycardia (120 beats per minute), and ST-segment elevation after recreational drug use.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary pathophysiological mechanism by which the suspected substance causes cardiovascular complications?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibition of voltage-gated sodium channels in cardiac myocytes","Blockade of norepinephrine and epinephrine reuptake at adrenergic nerve endings","Antagonism of GABA receptors in the central nervous system","Inhibition of acetylcholinesterase at neuromuscular junctions","Direct stimulation of beta-adrenergic receptors in cardiac tissue"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with cocaine-induced myocardial ischemia. The primary pathophysiological mechanism by which cocaine causes cardiovascular complications is through \u003Cstrong\u003Eblockade of norepinephrine and epinephrine reuptake at adrenergic nerve endings\u003C/strong\u003E. This leads to accumulation of these neurotransmitters in synapses, resulting in excessive sympathetic stimulation manifested as tachycardia, hypertension, and peripheral vasoconstriction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditionally, cocaine has two major effects on the cardiovascular system that can lead to myocardial ischemia:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIncreased myocardial oxygen demand due to tachycardia and hypertension\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDecreased coronary blood flow due to coronary artery vasoconstriction and enhanced platelet aggregation\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of acetylcholinesterase at neuromuscular junctions\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of action for organophosphate compounds and some nerve agents, not cocaine.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntagonism of GABA receptors in the central nervous system\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with substances like alcohol withdrawal or benzodiazepine antagonists, not cocaine.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect stimulation of beta-adrenergic receptors in cardiac tissue\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism for drugs like adrenaline or dobutamine. While cocaine indirectly increases catecholamine activity, it does not directly stimulate these receptors.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of voltage-gated sodium channels in cardiac myocytes\u003C/strong\u003E is a mechanism of action for some antiarrhythmic drugs. While cocaine does have some sodium channel blocking properties, this is not the primary mechanism for its cardiovascular effects.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImportantly, cocaine\u0027s cardiovascular toxicity is not necessarily dose-dependent, and serious complications including myocardial infarction can occur even in first-time users or with typical recreational doses.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Cocaine blocks the reuptake of dopamine in the CNS and both epinephrine and norepinephrine at adrenergic nerve endings.","The cardiovascular effects of cocaine are primarily due to its sympathomimetic activity, resulting in tachycardia, hypertension, and peripheral vasoconstriction.","Cocaine can induce myocardial ischemia through coronary artery vasoconstriction and enhanced platelet aggregation and thrombus formation."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 9; page 423-424."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77892"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20693"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77892"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-25T21:40:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-25T21:41:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13569"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94885"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":n